There&#39;s nothing stopping you from collecting the comparison results 
yourself prior to failing, e.g.

boolean[] testResult;
String result = &quot;&quot;;
for(int i=0;i &lt; testResult.length;i++) {
	result += testResult[i] ? &quot;F&quot; : &quot;.&quot;;
}

if (testResult.indexOf(&quot;F&quot;) != -1) {
	fail(&quot;At least one comparison failed: &quot; + testResult);
}

On Wednesday, August 14, 2002, at 10:12 AM, Chanoch Wiggers wrote:

&gt; You guys might be able to help me.
&gt;
&gt; I want to be able to determine dynamically the number of tests that
&gt; should be run. I have a number of tests to run that certain conditions
&gt; are met in the execution of a components. I don&#39;t want to write a test
&gt; per test condition because I don&#39;t know how many will be needed and I
&gt; don&#39;t want to rewrite the tests for each added (or removed condition). I
&gt; guess this resembles most closely an array contents test however I don&#39;t
&gt; know how many elements are present and the array equality argument
&gt; doesn&#39;t apply:
&gt;
&gt; The problem ofcourse is that if I loop through n conditions in a test,
&gt; the first one that fails will complete that test method but I want to
&gt; report multiple failures. The overall failure of the collection of
&gt; conditions is not a fine grained enough a report.
&gt;
&gt; Any ideas, pointers?
&gt;
&gt; thanks
&gt;
&gt; chanoch
