&gt; Please read all of the documentation.  To write a test, you simply
&gt; extend TestCase, add your &quot;public void testYYY()&quot; methods.  You can then
&gt; run this test case with anyone of the several TestRunners.  You can also
&gt; look at J.B.&#39;s excellent starter guide at
&gt; www.diasparsoftware.com/articles/JUnit/jUnitStarterGuide.html.
&gt;
&gt; =jason
&gt;
&gt; On Tue, 2002-08-13 at 20:11, Mert Nuhoglu wrote: Hello,
&gt;
&gt; I am a beginner to the JUnit framework. I didn&#39;t understand an issue
&gt; about the theory of JUnit.
&gt;
&gt; The test methods defined in a TestCase class are supposed to override
&gt; the runTest method. How do they do that?
&gt;
&gt; Let me explain what I understood. There are two ways:
&gt;
&gt; 1. According to the Adapter pattern with anonymous inner classes, each
&gt; test method is a subclass of the TestCase class.
&gt;
&gt; Quotation 1 (from A Cook&#39;s Tour):
&gt; TestCase test= new MoneyTest(&quot;testMoneyEquals &quot;) {
&gt;     protected void runTest() { testMoneyEquals(); }
&gt; };
&gt;
&gt; Here runTest method is explicitly overridden. But where is this code
&gt; segment written? Inside the static suite method?
&gt;
&gt; 2. According to the Pluggable Selector pattern, runTest method of
&gt; TestCase class of the JUnit framework handles everything. Right?
&gt;
&gt; Quotation 2 (from A Cook&#39;s Tour):
&gt; protected void runTest() throws Throwable {
&gt;     Method runMethod= null;
&gt;     try {
&gt;         runMethod= getClass().getMethod(fName, new Class[0]);
&gt;     } catch (NoSuchMethodException e) {
&gt;         assert(&quot;Method &#92;&quot;&quot;+fName+&quot;&#92;&quot; not found&quot;, false);
&gt;     }
&gt;     try {
&gt;         runMethod.invoke(this, new Class[0]);
&gt;     }
&gt;     // catch InvocationTargetException and IllegalAccessException
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; As far as I understood, runTest method reads somehow the name of the
&gt; test methods and invokes them.
&gt;
&gt; I would appreciate for your explanations...
&gt;
&gt; Best Regards.
&gt; Mert Nuhoglu
